        //   So `p[p_idx]` cannot be covered. Return `false`.
        //
        // Case 2: `head_left_reach > p[p_idx]`
        //   The current head is too far right to cover `p[p_idx]`.
        //   This means `p[p_idx]` must have been covered by a previous head.
        //   If `p[p_idx]` is still the leftmost uncovered track, it means it wasn't covered.
        //   So, `p[p_idx]` cannot be covered. Return `false`.
        //
        // Case 3: `head_left_reach <= p[p_idx] <= head_right_reach`
        //   The current head can cover `p[p_idx]`.
        //   It covers `p[p_idx]` and all subsequent tracks `p_j` such that `p_j <= head_right_reach`.
        //   Advance `p_idx` past all these covered tracks.
        //   `p_idx` becomes the index of the first track `p_k` such that `p_k > head_right_reach`.

        // This logic is correct.
        // The `p_idx` advancement can be done with `std::upper_bound`.

        // Example 1: h={2,5,6}, p={1,3,6,8}, T=2
        // p_idx = 0
        // h_idx = 0, h[0]=2. Range [2-2, 2+2] = [0, 4].
        //   p[0]=1. 0 <= 1 <= 4. Covers p[0]=1, p[1]=3.
        //   Advance p_idx: `upper_bound(p.begin()+0, p.end(), 4)` -> points to p[2]=6. So p_idx = 2.
        // p_idx = 2
        // h_idx = 1, h[1]=5. Range [5-2, 5+2] = [3, 7].
        //   p[2]=6. 3 <= 6 <= 7. Covers p[2]=6.
        //   Advance p_idx: `upper_bound(p.begin()+2, p.end(), 7)` -> points to p[3]=8. So p_idx = 3.
        // p_idx = 3
        // h_idx = 2, h[2]=6. Range [6-2, 6+2] = [4, 8].
        //   p[3]=8. 4 <= 8 <= 8. Covers p[3]=8.
        //   Advance p_idx: `upper_bound(p.begin()+3, p.end(), 8)` -> points to p.end(). So p_idx = 4.
        // p_idx = 4. Loop finishes.
        // After loop, p_idx == m (4 == 4). Return true.

        // Example 1: h={2,5,6}, p={1,3,6,8}, T=1
        // p_idx = 0
        // h_idx = 0, h[0]=2. Range [2-1, 2+1] = [1, 3].
        //   p[0]=1. 1 <= 1 <= 3. Covers p[0]=1, p[1]=3.
        //   Advance p_idx: `upper_bound(p.begin()+0, p.end(), 3)` -> points to p[2]=6. So p_idx = 2.
        // p_idx = 2
        // h_idx = 1, h[1]=5. Range [5-1, 5+1] = [4, 6].
        //   p[2]=6. 4 <= 6 <= 6. Covers p[2]=6.
        //   Advance p_idx: `upper_bound(p.begin()+2, p.end(), 6)` -> points to p[3]=8. So p_idx = 3.
        // p_idx = 3
        // h_idx = 2, h[2]=6. Range [6-1, 6+1] = [5, 7].
        //   p[3]=8. `head_right_reach` (7) < `p[p_idx]` (8).
        //   Case 1 applies. Return `false`.
        // Correct.

        // The logic seems solid.

        // Implementation details:
        // Binary search range for T:
        // Minimum T: 0 (if all p_i are already at h_i, or can be covered by existing h_i ranges).
        // Maximum T: `max(p_m-1, h_n-1) - min(p_0, h_0)`. A loose upper bound is `10^10`.
        // `10^10` is a safe upper bound for `T`.
        // `long long` for T, h_i, p_i.

        // Binary search:
        // `low = 0`, `high = 2e10` (a sufficiently large upper bound, e.g., max(p_i) - min(h_i) or max(h_i) - min(p_i) could be 10^10, so 2*10^10 is safe).
        // `ans = high`.
        // While `low <= high`:
        //   `mid = low + (high - low) / 2`.
        //   If `check(mid)` is true:
        //     `ans = mid`.
        //     `high = mid - 1`. (Try for smaller T)
        //   Else:
        //     `low = mid + 1`. (Need larger T)
        // Return `ans`.
    }

    return p_idx == m; // All tracks covered
}

int main() {
    std::ios_base::sync_with_stdio(false);
    std::cin.tie(NULL);

    int n, m;
    std::cin >> n >> m;

    std::vector<long long> h(n);
    for (int i = 0; i < n; ++i) {
        std::cin >> h[i];
    }

    std::vector<long long> p(m);
    for (int i = 0; i < m; ++i) {
        std::cin >> p[i];
    }

    long long low = 0;
    long long high = 20000000000LL; // Max possible difference between p_i and h_i is around 10^10.
                                    // A head might need to move from 1 to 10^10, so 10^10 is a good upper bound.
                                    // 2 * 10^10 is a safe upper bound for T.
    long long ans = high;

    while (low <= high) {
        long long mid = low + (high - low) / 2;
        if (check(mid, n, m, h, p)) {
            ans = mid;
            high = mid - 1;
        } else {
            low = mid + 1;
        }
    }

    std::cout << ans << std::endl;

    return 0;
}

#include <iostream>
