    // for a non-trivial palindrome.
    // A string s can be cut into s[0...i-1], s[i...j-1], s[j...N-1]
    // and reordered.
    // The problem statement implies that if a string is not all same characters,
    // then k=2 is always possible.
    // Example: "nolon" -> "no" | "l" | "on" -> "on" | "l" | "no" = "onlno" (palindrome)
    // This is achieved by swapping the first and last parts.
    // s = P1 P2 P3 ... Pk+1
    // We can always swap P1 and Pk+1 to get Pk+1 P2 ... Pk P1.
    // If s is a palindrome, then P1 is the reverse of Pk+1 (if P1 and Pk+1 are symmetric parts).
    // For k=2, we cut s into s[0...i-1], s[i...j-1], s[j...N-1].
    // Let P1 = s[0...i-1], P2 = s[i...j-1], P3 = s[j...N-1].
    // We can form P3 P2 P1.
    // If s is a palindrome, then s[0...i-1] is the reverse of s[N-i...N-1].
    // If we choose i = 1, j = N-1, then P1 = s[0], P2 = s[1...N-2], P3 = s[N-1].
    // The new string is s[N-1] + s[1...N-2] + s[0].
    // Since s is a palindrome, s[0] == s[N-1].
    // So s[N-1] + s[1...N-2] + s[0] is just s. This doesn't work.
    //
    // Consider the structure of a palindrome.
    // If all characters in s are the same (e.g., "qqqq"), then any reordering of pieces
    // will result in the same string "qqqq". In this case, it's impossible.
    //
    // If s contains at least two different characters, then k=2 is always possible.
    // Example: "abacaba"
    // Cut: "a" | "bacab" | "a"
    // Reorder: "a" | "bacab" | "a" (same string)
    //
    // The strategy for k=2 is to cut off a prefix and a suffix, and swap them.
    // Let s = P_prefix + P_middle + P_suffix.
    // If s is a palindrome, then P_prefix is the reverse of P_suffix.
    // If we swap P_prefix and P_suffix, we get P_suffix + P_middle + P_prefix.
    // This new string is a palindrome if P_middle is a palindrome.
    // And it will be different from s if P_prefix is not equal to P_suffix.
    // But P_prefix is reverse of P_suffix. So if P_prefix != P_suffix, then it's different.
    //
    // The example "nolon" -> "no" | "l" | "on" -> "on" | "l" | "no" = "onlno"
    // Here P_prefix = "no", P_middle = "l", P_suffix = "on".
    // "no" is not equal to "on".
    // "onlno" is a palindrome.
    //
    // This works if s is not of the form "aaaaa...".
    // If s is not all same characters, then there must be some character s[i] != s[0].
    // Consider the string s' = s[1...N-1] + s[0].
    // If s' is a palindrome and s' != s, then k=1. We already checked this.
    //
    // If s is not all same characters, then there exists some `i` such that `s[i] != s[0]`.
    // This means `s` is not of the form `c c c ... c`.
    // If `s` is not of the form `c c c ... c`, then we can always find a `k=2` solution.
    // Take `s = s_0 s_1 ... s_{N-1}`.
    // Since `s` is a palindrome, `s_0 = s_{N-1}`, `s_1 = s_{N-2}`, etc.
    // If `s` is not all same characters, then there exists some `i` such that `s_i != s_0`.
    // This implies `s_i != s_{N-1}`.
    //
    // Consider cutting `s` into `s[0]`, `s[1...N-2]`, `s[N-1]`.
    // Let `P1 = s[0]`, `P2 = s[1...N-2]`, `P3 = s[N-1]`.
    // Since `s` is a palindrome, `s[0] == s[N-1]`.
    // Reordering `P3 P2 P1` gives `s[N-1] + s[1...N-2] + s[0]`, which is `s`. This doesn't work.
    //
    // The example "nolon" (N=5)
    // s[0]='n', s[1]='o', s[2]='l', s[3]='o', s[4]='n'
    // Cut: "no" | "l" | "on"
