        //
        // Let's re-state the property:
        // For each `i`, `p[i]` is either `max_{j!=i} a[i][j]` OR `n`.
        // More precisely:
        // `p[i] = max_{j!=i} a[i][j]` if `p[i]` is NOT `n`.
        // `p[i] = n` if `max_{j!=i} a[i][j]` is `n-1` AND `p[i]` is `n`.
        //
        // This means that if `max_{j!=i} a[i][j]` is `n-1`, then `p[i]` is either `n` or `n-1`.
        // If `max_{j!=i} a[i][j]` is `X < n-1`, then `p[i]` must be `X`.
        //
        // So, we can determine `p[i]` for all `i` where `max_{j!=i} a[i][j] < n-1`.
        // For these `i`, `p[i] = max_{j!=i} a[i][j]`.
        //
        // What about the `i` where `max_{j!=i} a[i][j] == n-1`?
        // For these `i`, `p[i]` is either `n` or `n-1`.
        // There must be exactly one `p[k] = n`.
        // There must be exactly one `p[l] = n-1`.
        //
        // Let `S = {i | max_{j!=i} a[i][j] == n-1}`.
        // All `i` not in `S` have `p[i] = max_{j!=i} a[i][j]`.
        // For `i` in `S`, one of them must be `n`, and the other (if `|S|>1`) must be `n-1`.
        //
        // Example `n=5`, `a` given.
        // `n-1 = 4`.
        // `M_0 = max(2,2,1,2) = 2`. So `p[0]=2`.
        // `M_1 = max(2,4,1,3) = 4`. So `p[1]` is either `5` or `4`.
        // `M_2 = max(2,4,1,3) = 4`. So `p[2]` is either `5` or `4`.
        // `M_3 = max(1,1,1,1) = 1`. So `p[3]=1`.
        // `M_4 = max(2,3,3,1) = 3`. So `p[4]=3`.
        //
        // So far: `p = {2, ?, ?, 1, 3}`.
        // The values `1,2,3` are used. `4,5` are remaining.
        // `S = {1, 2}`.
        // One of `p[1], p[2]` must be `5`, the other `4`.
        // We can assign `p[1]=5, p[2]=4` or `p[1]=4, p[2]=5`.
        // The example output is `2 5 4 1 3`. This matches `p[1]=5, p[2]=4`.
        //
        // This strategy seems robust.
        // 1. Compute `M_i = max_{j!=i} a[i][j]` for all `i`.
        // 2. Create a `std::vector<int> p(n)`.
        // 3. Create a `std::vector<int> candidates_for_n_n_minus_1`.
        // 4. For `i = 0 to n-1`:
        //    If `M_i == n-1`: add `i` to `candidates_for_n_n_minus_1`.
        //    Else (`M_i < n-1`): `p[i] = M_i`.
        // 5. Now `candidates_for_n_n_minus_1` contains indices whose `p` values are `n` or `n-1`.
        //    There are two cases:
        //    a) `candidates_for_n_n_minus_1.size() == 1`. Let this index be `k`.
        //       Then `p[k] = n`. (This happens if `n-1` was already assigned to some `p[i]` where `M_i = n-1` was not true, which is impossible).
        //       This case implies that `n-1` was assigned to some `p[i]` where `M_i < n-1`.
        //       This is also impossible.
        //       So, if `|S|=1`, say `S={k}`, then `p[k]=n`. But what about `n-1`?
        //       This means `n-1` was assigned to some `p[i]` where `M_i = n-1` was not true.
        //       This is impossible.
        //       The only way `n-1` is not in `S` is if `p[i]=n-1` and `M_i = n-1`.
        //       So `|S|` must be at least 2 if `n > 2`.
        //       If `n=2`, `S={0,1}`.
        //
        // Let's rethink the `n=2` case.
        // `n=2`, `a={{0,1},{1,0}}`.
        // `M_0 = 1`, `M_1 = 1`.
        // `n-1 = 1`.
        // `candidates_for_n_n_minus_1 = {0, 1}`.
        // `p` is unassigned.
        // We need to assign `p[0]` and `p[1]` to `1` and `2`.
        // The problem says "any permutation". So `p[0]=2, p[1]=1` is fine.
        //
        // For `n > 2`:
        // `M_i = p[i]` if `p[i] < n`.
        // `M_i = n-1` if `p[i] = n`.
        //
        // So, for all `i` where `M_i < n-1`, we know `p[i] = M_i`.
        // For all `i` where `M_i = n-1`, `p[i]` is either `n` or `n-1`.
        // There will be exactly one `i` for which `p[i]=n`. For this `i`, `M_i=n-1`.
        // There will be exactly one `i` for which `p[i]=n-1`. For this `i`, `M_i` could be `n-1` (if `n-1` is not the smallest value) or `n-2` (if `n-1` is the smallest value).
        //
        // This is the key: `max_{j!=i} min(p[i], p[j])`.
        // If `p[i] = k`:
        //   If `k=n`: `max_{j!=i} min(n, p[j]) = max_{j!=i} p[j] = n-1`.
        //   If `k < n`: `max_{j!=i} min(k, p[j])`. This value is `k` if there exists some `p[j'] > k`.
        //     This is always true for `k < n` because `n` is in the permutation.
        //     So, if `p[i] < n`, then `max_{j!=i} min(p[i], p[j]) = p[i]`.
        //
        // This means:
        // If `max_val_for_i == n-1`, then `p[i]` must be `n`.
        // If `max_val_for_i < n-1`, then `p[i]` must be `max_val_for_i`.
        //
        // This logic is correct and simpler.
        // Let's re-test `n=2`, `a={{0,1},{1,0}}`.
        // `n-1 = 1`.
        // `M_0 = 1`. `M_0 == n-1` is true. So `p[0]=n=2`.
        // `M_1 = 1`. `M_1 == n-1` is true. So `p[1]=n=2`.
        // Result `p={2,2}`. Still wrong.
        //
        // The problem is that for `n=2`, `p={1,2}`:
        // `p[0]=1`. `max_{j!=0} min(p[0], p[j]) = min(1,2) = 1`.
        // `p[1]=2`. `max_{j!=1} min(p[1], p[j]) = min(2,1) = 1`.
        // In this case, `max_val_for_i` is `1` for both `i=0` and `i=1`.
        // And `n-1` is also `1`.
        // So the condition `max_val_for_i == n-1` is true for both `i=0` and `i=1`.
        // This means my simple logic assigns `p[i]=n` for both, which is wrong.
        //
        // The simple logic `p[i] = max_val_for_i` if `max_val_for_i < n-1` is correct.
        // The problem is when `max_val_for_i == n-1`.
        //
        // If `n > 2`:
        //   Exactly one `p[k]` is `n`. For this `k`, `max_val_for_k = n-1`.
        //   Exactly one `p[l]` is `n-1`. For this `l`, `max_val_for_l = n-1` (because `n` is present).
        //   So there are exactly two indices `k, l` for which `max_val_for_i = n-1`.
        //   One of them is `n`, the other is `n-1`.
        //   We can assign `p[k]=n` and `p[l]=n-1` arbitrarily.
        //
        // If `n = 2`:
        //   `p={1,2}`.
        //   `p[0]=1`, `max_val_for_0 = 1`.
        //   `p[1]=2`, `max_val_for_1 = 1`.
        //   Both `max_val_for_i` are `n-1`.
        //   We need to assign `p[0]=1, p[1]=2` or `p[0]=2, p[1]=1`.
        //
        // So the strategy is:
        // 1. Compute `M_i = max_{j!=i} a[i][j]` for all `i`.
        // 2. Create `std::vector<int> p(n)`.
        // 3. Create `std::vector<int> indices_with_n_minus_1_max`.
        // 4. For `i = 0 to n-1`:
        //    If `M_i == n-1`: add `i` to `indices_with_n_minus_1_max`.
        //    Else (`M_i < n-1`): `p[i] = M_i`.
        // 5. After the loop:
        //    If `indices_with_n_minus_1_max.size() == 1`:
        //       Let `k = indices_with_n_minus_1_max[0]`.
        //       `p[k] = n`. (This case implies `n-1` was already assigned to some `p[i]` where `M_i < n-1`, which is impossible).
        //       This case should not happen for `n > 2`.
        //       If `n=2`, `indices_with_n_minus_1_max.size()` will be 2.
        //       So this case implies `n-1` is not present in the permutation, which is impossible.
        //       This case means that `n-1` was assigned to some `p[i]` where `M_i < n-1`.
        //       This is impossible.
        //       The only way `|indices_with_n_minus_1_max|` is 1 is if `n-1` is not present in the permutation, or `n-1` is the smallest value.
        //       If `n-1` is the smallest value (i.e., `n-1=1`, so `n=2`), then `M_i` for `p[i]=1` is `1`, and `M_i` for `p[i]=2` is `1`.
        //       So `|indices_with_n_minus_1_max|` is 2 for `n=2`.
        //       So `|indices_with_n_minus_1_max|` is always 2 for `n >= 2`.
        //       One of them is `n`, the other is `n-1`.
        //
        // Final refined strategy:
        // 1. Compute `M_i = max_{j!=i} a[i][j]` for all `i`.
        // 2. Create `std::vector<int> p(n)`.
        // 3. Create `std::vector<int> indices_to_assign_n_and_n_minus_1`.
        // 4. For `i = 0 to n-1`:
        //    If `M_i == n-1`:
        //       `indices_to_assign_n_and_n_minus_1.push_back(i)`.
        //    Else:
        //       `p[i] = M_i`.
        // 5. Now, `indices_to_assign_n_and_n_minus_1` contains the indices that should be assigned `n` and `n-1`.
        //    There will be exactly two such indices (unless `n=1`, which is not allowed).
        //    Let these indices be `idx1` and `idx2`.
        //    Assign `p[idx1] = n` and `p[idx2] = n-1`. (Order doesn't matter for "any permutation").
        //
        // Let's test this strategy:
        // Example 1: `n=2`, `a={{0,1},{1,0}}`.
        // `M_0 = 1`, `M_1 = 1`.
        // `n-1 = 1`.
        // `indices_to_assign_n_and_n_minus_1 = {0, 1}`.
        // `p` is unassigned.
        // `idx1 = 0`, `idx2 = 1`.
        // `p[0] = n = 2`.
        // `p[1] = n-1 = 1`.
        // Output: `2 1`. Correct.
        //
        // Example 2: `n=5`, `a` given.
        // `n-1 = 4`.
        // `M_0 = 2`. `p[0]=2`.
        // `M_1 = 4`. `indices_to_assign_n_and_n_minus_1.push_back(1)`.
        // `M_2 = 4`. `indices_to_assign_n_and_n_minus_1.push_back(2)`.
        // `M_3 = 1`. `p[3]=1`.
        // `M_4 = 3`. `p[4]=3`.
        //
        // `p = {2, ?, ?, 1, 3}`.
        // `indices_to_assign_n_and_n_minus_1 = {1, 2}`.
        // `idx1 = 1`, `idx2 = 2`.
        // `p[1] = n = 5`.
        // `p[2] = n-1 = 4`.
        // Output: `2 5 4 1 3`. Correct.
        //
        // This strategy seems correct and covers all cases.

    std::vector<int> max_vals_for_i(n);
    for (int i = 0; i < n; ++i) {
        int current_max = 0;
        for (int j = 0; j < n; ++j) {
            if (i != j) {
                current_max = std::max(current_max, a[i][j]);
            }
        }
        max_vals_for_i[i] = current_max;
    }

    std::vector<int> result_p(n);
    std::vector<int> indices_for_n_and_n_minus_1;

    for (int i = 0; i < n; ++i) {
        if (max_vals_for_i[i] == n - 1) {
            indices_for_n_and_n_minus_1.push_back(i);
        } else {
            result_p[i] = max_vals_for_i[i];
        }
    }

    // At this point, indices_for_n_and_n_minus_1 should contain exactly two indices.
    // One corresponds to 'n', the other to 'n-1'.
    // For n=2, max_vals_for_i will be {1,1}. n-1=1. So indices_for_n_and_n_minus_1 will be {0,1}.
    // For n>2, max_vals_for_i for p[k]=n is n-1. max_vals_for_i for p[l]=n-1 is n-1.
    // All other p[x] < n-1 will have max_vals_for_x = p[x].
    // So there will be exactly two indices in indices_for_n_and_n_minus_1.
    // We can assign n to the first one and n-1 to the second one.
    result_p[indices_for_n_and_n_minus_1[0]] = n;
    result_p[indices_for_n_and_n_minus_1[1]] = n - 1;

    for (int i = 0; i < n; ++i) {
        std::cout << result_p[i] << (i == n - 1 ? "" : " ");
    }
    std::cout << std::endl;

    return 0;
}

#include <iostream>
#include <string>
#include <vector>
#include <numeric>
#include <algorithm>

void solve() {
    long long A, B, C, D;
    std::cin >> A >> B >> C >> D;

    std::vector<std::string> result(4);

    // Total number of toys
    long long total_toys = A + B + C + D;

    // Case 1: Only one toy initially
    if (total_toys == 1) {
        result[0] = (A == 1) ? "Ya" : "Tidak";
        result[1] = (B == 1) ? "Ya" : "Tidak";
        result[2] = (C == 1) ? "Ya" : "Tidak";
        result[3] = (D == 1) ? "Ya" : "Tidak";
        std::cout << result[0] << " " << result[1] << " " << result[2] << " " << result[3] << std::endl;
        return;
    }

    // Determine the sign of the final product
    // If (A + B) is odd, final product is negative.
    // If (A + B) is even, final product is positive.
    bool final_is_negative = ((A + B) % 2 != 0);

    // Determine if magnitude can be < 1
    // This requires at least one toy with magnitude < 1 (from B or C)
    // AND it must be possible to "overcome" any toys with magnitude >= 1 (from A or D).
    // If there are no toys with magnitude >= 1 (A=0, D=0), then the magnitude can always be < 1
    // if there's at least one B or C toy.
    // If there are toys with magnitude >= 1, we need to be able to multiply them by enough B/C toys
    // to bring the magnitude below 1.
    // This is possible if B+C > 0.
    // Exception: If A+D > 0 and B+C = 0, then magnitude will always be >= 1.
    bool can_be_mag_lt_1 = (B + C > 0);

    // Determine if magnitude can be >= 1
    // This requires at least one toy with magnitude >= 1 (from A or D)
    // OR it requires B+C >= 2 (to multiply two small values to get a small value, then multiply by another small value to get an even smaller value, etc.)
    // If A+D > 0, then magnitude can be >= 1.
    // If A+D = 0, then all initial toys have magnitude < 1.
    // In this case, the product of any number of such toys will also have magnitude < 1.
    // So, if A+D = 0, magnitude cannot be >= 1.
    bool can_be_mag_ge_1 = (A + D > 0);

    // Special case for A=0, D=0: all initial toys have magnitude < 1.
    // The final product will always have magnitude < 1.
    if (A == 0 && D == 0) {
        can_be_mag_ge_1 = false;
    }

    // Special case for B=0, C=0: all initial toys have magnitude >= 1.
    // The final product will always have magnitude >= 1.
    if (B == 0 && C == 0) {
        can_be_mag_lt_1 = false;
    }

    // Box 1: Negative, magnitude >= 1
    if (final_is_negative && can_be_mag_ge_1) {
        result[0] = "Ya";
    } else {
        result[0] = "Tidak";
    }

    // Box 2: Negative, magnitude < 1
    if (final_is_negative && can_be_mag_lt_1) {
        result[1] = "Ya";
    } else {
        result[1] = "Tidak";
    }

    // Box 3: Positive, magnitude < 1
    if (!final_is_negative && can_be_mag_lt_1) {
        result[2] = "Ya";
    } else {
        result[2] = "Tidak";
    }

    // Box 4: Positive, magnitude >= 1
    if (!final_is_negative && can_be_mag_ge_1) {
        result[3] = "Ya";
    } else {
        result[3] = "Tidak";
    }

    // Edge case: If A+D=0, then all initial toys are in B or C.
    // The final product will always have magnitude < 1.
    // So Box 1 and Box 4 are impossible.
    if (A == 0 && D == 0) {
        result[0] = "Tidak";
        result[3] = "Tidak";
    }

    // Edge case: If B+C=0, then all initial toys are in A or D.
    // The final product will always have magnitude >= 1.
    // So Box 2 and Box 3 are impossible.
    if (B == 0 && C == 0) {
        result[1] = "Tidak";
        result[2] = "Tidak";
    }

    std::cout << result[0] << " " << result[1] << " " << result[2] << " " << result[3] << std::endl;
}

